2720427416159296.author: Coral
2720427416159296.content:
This fall, a number of cities around the world will celebrate the openings of major new museums—many of them with architecture as worthy of awe as the art itself. Some openings, like the Jean Nouvel–designed Louvre Abu Dhabi, will be seismic events for the architectural world. Others, like the Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art in Jakarta, signal the maturation of their country’s flourishing arts scenes into subjects of international interest. From Cape Town’s Zeitz Museum—the first major museum in Africa devoted exclusively to contemporary art—to the Bible Museum in Washington, D.C., where visitors can roam a garden filled with plants referenced in the good book, the next few months will bring a bounty of new places to wander, learn, and find inspiration for years to come.

2723737984418880.author: Coral
2723737984418880.content:
Where are the most expensive residential housing prices in Europe? Where has the biggest increase and the most investment value? Deloitte’s recent European residential housing market house price index report shows that among more than ten European countries where the residential real estate market is more popular, the average housing price in Germany increased by 9.6% compared with the previous year in 2017, the largest increase in the United Kingdom. The decline was the largest, down 5%.


However, the central area of ​​the British capital London is still the most expensive place in Europe, with an average price of more than 16,000 euros (approximately 126,500 yuan) per square meter. UK residential housing prices continue to rank first in Europe at a price of nearly 4,400 euros (about 34,700 yuan) per square meter.


In terms of per capita income, among the countries surveyed by the aforementioned index, the Czechs are the most difficult to buy a house in Europe. Residents in this country need to work 11.3 years to buy a 70-square-meter apartment, while Britons need to work an average of 9.8 years. The difficulty of buying a house closely follows the Czech Republic.

﻿
2723737984418880.title: European real estate investment：London is the most expensive in Europe, and Germany has the fastest increase.

2759188565877824.author: Coral
2759188565877824.content:
According to the report, the European economy grew well in 2017, with the GDP growth rate of the 28 EU countries reaching 2.6%, and the Eurozone growth rate of 2.5%. The European Central Bank's loose monetary policy and extremely low mortgage interest rates have supported the rise in housing prices.


The current interest rate on mortgages in the Eurozone is still at the lowest level in history. Portugal has the lowest mortgage interest rate in Europe, with an average of only 1%, France is only about 1.5%, and the mortgage interest rates in Austria, Germany, the United Kingdom, the Czech Republic, Italy, and Belgium remain around 2%. However, the report believes that taking into account the high probability of interest rate hikes in the euro area next year, mortgage interest rates will gradually rise.
2759188565877824.title: Belgian can buy a house after 3.7 years of work

2778223746688064.author: Coral Zhang
2778223746688064.content:
House prices in Europe's major cities have risen sharply since 2012, but at the same time wages per person have lagged far behind.

According to research published last week by Moody's, the US credit rating agency, it takes about 15 years to buy a medium-sized property in Europe on salary and without food or drink.

That figure averages rural areas where housing prices are low, but it may take longer in big cities.

But even so, Europe is a lot better than at home.

In first-tier cities, Shanghai, for example, the average annual salary of urban non-private sector employees was 105,176 yuan in 2019, according to the Shanghai Municipal Human Resources and Social Security Bureau. According to the latest data from Anjuke, the average housing price in Shanghai in 2019 is about 50,773 yuan /m².

According to this calculation, it takes at least 30 years to buy a 60m² house in Shanghai, and the 60m² house here includes the public share. The situation is similar in Beijing and Shanghai.

Even in lower-priced cities, where incomes are relatively low, it still takes nearly 15 years.




However, in Europe, although the housing prices in major cities in Europe have increased in recent years, the average age of buying a house in Europe is much lower than that in China. In addition, the low mortgage interest rate in Europe recently makes more people have the economic strength to buy the desired property.
2778223746688064.title: How many years does the average European citizen work to buy a house? Spain is the fastest of the four！
